AD311 – Third‑Party API Integration Write‑Up
API Chosen
For this project, I selected the Cat Facts API (https://catfact.ninja/fact). I chose this API because it is simple, requires no authentication, and returns lightweight JSON data that is easy to integrate into a small web application. It also allowed me to focus on the core assignment goals: making a fetch request, handling responses, updating the UI, and demonstrating error handling.

Application Overview
My application is a Random Cat Fact Generator. When the user clicks a button, the app sends a request to the Cat Facts API and displays a new fact on the page. The interface includes:

A button to fetch a new fact

A display area for the fact

A loading state

Error handling for offline mode, blocked requests, and failed fetches

The goal was to create a simple, clean UI that clearly shows the result of each API call.

How the Application Works
The user clicks Get Cat Fact.

The app shows a temporary “Loading…” message.

A fetch() request is sent to the API endpoint.

If successful, the JSON response is parsed and displayed on the page.

If the request fails (network error, timeout, blocked request), the app displays an error message and logs the error in the console.

The app uses only HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, and runs entirely in the browser.

Normal Test Cases
These demonstrate expected behavior when everything is working:

Clicking the button returns a cat fact

The UI updates with a new fact.

Console logs the JSON response.

Multiple clicks return different facts

Each request fetches a new fact from the API.

Page loads and fetch works with no errors

The app behaves normally with a stable internet connection.

Edge Test Cases
These demonstrate how the app handles failures, as required by the assignment:

Internet disconnected

DevTools shows: net::ERR_INTERNET_DISCONNECTED

UI displays an error message.

Console logs the caught error.

API request blocked in DevTools

Using Network → Block Request URL

The fetch fails and triggers the error handler.

Simulated timeout using Network Throttling (Slow 3G)

The request takes too long and eventually fails.

The app shows the error message and logs the failure.

These tests confirm that the application handles unexpected conditions gracefully.

Challenges Encountered
Understanding fetch error behavior:  
The API doesn’t always return an HTTP error—sometimes the browser throws a generic TypeError: Failed to fetch. I had to test different failure scenarios to understand how to catch and display these errors properly.

Simulating edge cases:  
I used DevTools features like Offline mode, Request Blocking, and Network Throttling to create realistic failure conditions.

Ensuring clean UI updates:  
I added loading states and clear error messages so the user always knows what’s happening.

Conclusion
This project helped me practice integrating a third‑party API, handling asynchronous requests, and designing UI behavior around both successful and failed responses. The application meets the assignment requirements by demonstrating API usage, proper error handling, documentation, and a video walkthrough showing normal and edge test cases.
